56","1405–1488":"1405–1488","1407–1475":"1407–1475","1349–1407":"1349–1407","1354–1410":"1354–1410","16 May 1378":"16 mei 1378","4 October 1440":"4 oktober 1440","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1403":"1403","1456":"1456","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1354":"1354","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St. Mary's Churchyard, Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, England","Westhorpe, Suffolk, England":"Westhorpe, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1378–4 October 1440":"1378–4 October 1440","1376–1420":"1376–1420","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1382–1456":"1382–1456","1405–1488":"1405–1488","1407–1475":"1407–1475","1349–1407":"1349–1407","1354–1410":"1354–1410","16 May 1378":"16 May 1378","4 October 1440":"4 October 1440","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1403":"1403","1456":"1456","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1354":"1354","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","St. Mary's Churchyard, Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, England","Westhorpe, Suffolk, England":"Westhorpe, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pratyman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Prettyman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Prettyman","meanings":["English (Suffolk): nickname from Middle English <i>prat(e)</i>, <i>pratte</i> ‘cunning, wily’ (Old English <i>prætt</i>) + <i>man</i>, or an occupational name signifying the servant (Middle English ‘man’) of someone named   Pretty  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":4,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Pratyman was born in 1378, in Bacton, Suffolk, England, his father, William Pratyman, was 30 and his mother, Agnes Hobart, was 25. He married Agnes Howlett in 1403, in Bacton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 4 October 1440, in his hometown, at the age of 62, and was buried in Bacton, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1378–4 October 1440":"1378–4. oktoober 1440","1376–1420":"1376–1420","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1382–1456":"1382–1456","1405–1488":"1405–1488","1407–1475":"1407–1475","1349–1407":"1349–1407","1354–1410":"1354–1410","16 May 1378":"16. mai 1378","4 October 1440":"4. oktoober 1440","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1403":"1403","1456":"1456","1378":"1378","1488":"1488","1410":"1410","1354":"1354","1475":"1475","1420":"1420","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","1407":"1407","1405":"1405","Bacton, Suffolk, England":"Bacton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St. Mary's Church